''See also [[säd]]''
==English==
===Pronunciation===
*[[IPA]]: /sæd/
===Etymology===
Derived from Old English '''sæd''', literally meaning "sated", and later meaning "weary."
===Adjective===
'''sad''' ({{compar}}: '''[[sadder]]''', {{superl}}: '''[[saddest]]''')
# feeling mentally uncomfortable when something is missing or wrong.
#: ''She gets '''sad''' when he's away.''
# low in spirits, melancholy.
#: ''♬ Poor puppy, you look so '''sad'''… ♬''
# (''of a song, etc.'') moving, full of feeling.
#: ''The Great Gaels of Ireland God truely made mad.''
#: ''For, all their wars are merry and all their songs are '''sad'''.'' ―G.K. Chesterton
# poor in quality, lacking in character.
#: ''That's the '''saddest'''-looking pickup truck I've ever seen.''
====Synonyms====
#[[unhappy]]
#[[glum]], [[down in the dumps]]
#[[poignant]], [[touching]]
#[[pitiful]], [[sorry]]
====Antonyms====
#[[happy]]
#[[cheerful]]
#[[gleeful]], [[upbeat]]
#[[decent]]

